headline_main: Notre-Dame, Columbine, Beyoncé: Your Wednesday Briefing

abstract: Millions of Americans are using this powdered leaf, saying it alleviates PTSD, addiction and other ills. The federal government may want to ban it.
snippet: Millions of Americans are using this powdered leaf, saying it alleviates PTSD, addiction and other ills. The federal government may want to ban it.
lead_paragraph: The steep rise in the number of people suffering opioid addiction has helped spawn the widespread use of another substance: kratom, a green powdered herbal supplement that is widely available and virtually unregulated.

headline_main: Notre-Dame, Royal Family, Nissan: Your Wednesday Briefing

abstract: Senator Elizabeth Warren has spent millions to build her campaign staff, while Mayor Pete Buttigieg spent less than 10 percent of what he raised in the first quarter.
snippet: Senator Elizabeth Warren has spent millions to build her campaign staff, while Mayor Pete Buttigieg spent less than 10 percent of what he raised in the first quarter.
lead_paragraph: Some Democratic candidates for president are already spending furiously to saturate Facebook with ads as they race to qualify for the first debates this summer. Others are carefully husbanding their resources, banking cash in hopes of unloading it in a burst as the primaries near.

abstract: In speeches, in interviews and on Twitter this week, the president has been a kind of town crier as he opines on the day’s news developments.
snippet: In speeches, in interviews and on Twitter this week, the president has been a kind of town crier as he opines on the day’s news developments.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As he awaits the Thursday release of the redacted special counsel report on his 2016 campaign’s ties to Russia, President Trump is filling his idle moments — and blowing off any anticipatory steam — by turning to a familiar pastime: television.
